            <p>The experience on smaller screens gave us an excuse to work with the development team on designing and coding gestures. Swiping from hotel to hotel is a natural, expected gesture.</p>
            <p>Design details matter. Panel edges hint at distinct hotel brands using color and shape, and imply swiping. A fixed header persists the Close button no matter the scroll. Tappable content invokes maps and phone calls.</p>
            <p>For a team unfamiliar with gesture-based interaction, demonstrating the experience via a fully-coded prototype provoked useful questions of “What gestures go where?” and “What script libraries do we need for these features?”</p>
            <h3>Revealing Hotel Brands within Immersive Maps</h3>
            <p>Maps proved an exciting challenge too. Maps? Why maps? Doesn’t Google do maps, like really well? Yes, but [as Marriott learned in prior research] mapping is essential to finding just the right hotel.</p>
            <p>On the desktop, we sought to make the map bigger. Way bigger. Break the layout grid’s max-width of 1024px bigger. The map dominated the desktop browser’s view, extending to the canvas’ max width of 1400px. The massive map size also afforded more space for the panel of hotel details, focusing users on the central task.</p>
